', 'Louise Mills née Bahlsen was my great great grandmother. Louise was born and trained in Lübeck, Germany as a mezzo-soprano. She met John Henry Mills, a British merchant marine 14 years her senior and were inexplicably married at two tiny Catholic churches along the coast of Chile in 1867(!) She became a professor of music in Liverpool. My great grandfather Alfred John, born in 1888, was their only child. John died at sea around 1891.
The next records are of Louise and Alfred leaving Liverpool for Montreal on the SS Parisian in 1898. I been lucky enough to find her in many exhaustive British newspaper archives. ', 'After the ho’ike at Nahiku Hawaiian Church I headed off towards Hana, intending to drive through the Kaupo side to get back to the valley. Stopped off at Hana for a bit to check out their Festivals of Aloha, which was taking place this weekend. Parked near my favorite promontory overlooking Hana Bay, walked over to the edge of the cliff to take in the view. There were three local boys there, pensively looking out towards the ocean and approaching rain squall, about the age of the boy who died earlier last week. After looking quietly out a bit, I turned and said to them, “Hey guys, so sorry to hear about Jre.” Jredyn Kaina was a high school freshman, who succumbed on Tuesday to injuries from a serious crash in his ATV the weekend before. One of them said, “Yeah uncle… so sad.” And after a pause, “How you heard about it, uncle?” seeing as I clearly wasn’t from Hana.

I related to them how I was part of the officiating crew at the MIL Girls Volleyball tournament semifinal on Thursday evening at Seabury Hall, between their Hana High School girls varsity team versus Moloka’i. And that onlookers had posters of Jre emblazoned with “Play for Jre, Tyra-Li!” and other such sentiments. And that after the game, which Hana won, instead of celebratory cheers the girls—from both teams—burst out in tears, crying and sobbing in long, tight hugs with family and friends.

Someone’s death is always a sad thing but when it happens to one’s teenage peer—and a beloved aunty or uncle’s son or sibling—is particularly hard to bear. It was evident at Erdman Gym that evening, applying a thick veneer of tragedy to what should have been an upbeat, competitive scene.

I told the boys how it was such a strange and painful flashback for me. Shared with them how, in 2014, the year my hanai son Pono was a senior in high school, the week before his Kamehameha Schools varsity boys volleyball team was to play in the season tournament, a player from Hana HS, senior Isaiah Pu-Akima died when his car went over a guardrail on Hana Highway, plunging hundreds of feet down to the ocean. The boys nodded sadly, saying they remembered what happened with Isaiah as well.

', 'Hmm. There’s a spot along this ragged curve of seacliff where an incoming wave hits it and then its energy radiates back out at an angle—still in the form of a wave—and meets the next wave in the set at an acute angle. Where the lines meet, an extraordinary pyramid forms precipitously, rising to a vertex much higher than a regular wave’s peak crest. It’s shocking to see, especially the first time one sees it. So of course I have an idea for an image at this same time of day, but it requires some risk—of going down to the level of those rocks, but at a place secure enough where one can’t be swept out by the largest wave of the set. I’m not sure a mere iPhone camera can capture what my mind’s eye is seeing, but I can try. Will be monitoring the surf reports for the next couple of weeks or so, as this photographic attempt will require a substantial swell. Must also take note of the tides, as the highest tide will surely preclude this attempt. May have to bring a rope as well, to tether myself to the cliff, just in case my chanting wasn’t loud enough to be heard by the relevant gods. ;-)

', 'The season’s approaching demiurge bade me look, but obliquely. I initially had no idea what she was talking about, but she persisted in that near-soundless undulating hum—a waveform that interpenetrates everything, like laminar flow or fractals—that makes this place capture me so…  so I took an image I had just taken and turned it ninety degrees, looking at it as if I were lain down on my side, aground. The world is full of the banal and the beautiful—and often enough these elements of the world are both at once. The voice in my head signifies that I am either a really good listener… or am rather quickly devolving into the lunacy of my nether years. ::chuckle:: She has a way of conveying to me what is obvious in sublime fashion; but, also, getting me to see the subtle nature of things in language so pedestrian as to be instantly missed. So I ask of you dear interlocutor: lie down on your side awhile, go askance and, as the hoa pili have been saying of late… hulihia! { Lonoikamakahiki! }

How could they have known I had been looking for something to signal my car as a Maunakea kia’i? :-) I’m not exactly a hae Hawai’i-waving kanaka, nor am I into emblazoning my bumpers with stickers or prone to writing mauna slogans on my windows. ", 'Held 'Aha Awakea here again this noon, after cuz @kaaihueahpuck sold me one of his own Apolima that he was wearing on his arm—mahalo nui loa, kia'i! I was doing the pule, oli, mele and hula by myself until this little kid came over and sat by the red kia'i pareo that I'd lain on the stony beach. Earlier, he'd been chatting with cuz Konapiliahi in fluent Hawaiian. Kona said he and many kids from the valley attend the Hawaiian Immersion program at Princess Nahienaena Elementary in Lahaina. So anyway, the kid (what did you say his name was, cuz?)—who was no older than kindergarten—just sat there near me, playing with the ili'ili and a couple of sticks... and watching me chant "O Hanau Ka Mauna." But when that was pau and I started dancing "Maunakea Kuahiwi," he began singing along—with perfect fluency and pitch! If you can imagine a barefoot little boy—blonde, blue-eyed... singing in Hawaiian along with my dancing, you can imagine both my delight and feeling of extraordinary grace. Kānaka truly manifest in many forms, don't they?

', '1... earlier today:

It makes a difference, that I am alone here at Kūkaniloko. (It’s still quite early in the morning, about an hour after sunrise and no one’s here yet; although, I don’t imagine many tourists or visitors come by on any given day.) I feel the mana of the place the instant I walk past the barrier across the unpaved roadway leading into the site itself. Were I resident here on O’ahu I would most definitely frequent this place to seek the ancient visions and, perhaps to learn the olden chants. They echo here still—for anyone with pepeiao to hear, maka to see, na’au to feel. And so I step through… yet another portal… and am blessed with the voice of the makani sweeping through the central plateau of this island, and the mālie of the dome of sky above—which I know, in the brightness of this morning, is filled with the language of time itself in the points, lines, arcs and geometries of the hōkū… when the earth whirls back to the dark of night. It is with unspeakable gratitude, that I am awed.

', 'As I stand here watching Venus dragging Kāne angularly upwards with her invisible tether—see the diamond pixel above and to the right of the scimitar moon—I find myself curiously stricken. The feeling is impossible to articulate properly, so freighted and fraught it is with everything. So I will let this image suffice, to remind me of the moment … and the magnitude of things-as-they-are. These things will have to be cryptic for now, for reason. In due time they will be clear enough; and, as I contemplate the pastel skyscape of subtlest light playing on the transparent scrim of the sky, I reckon that time to be precious indeed. {Once upon a time, there was a boy. Born into an archipelagic life, he found himself strung into a myriad of histories, as befit his existence in a skein of islands large and small. Once upon the future, he would find himself settled on just the one island and, with that settling, find the singular resolution to the many, ephemeral, stories.}

', 'After-church lunch, after a leisurely drive along the north coast—am house-sitting in Far Haiku for Shay and Ian, who are in London with Kean and Liam—was at the food trucks in the Haiku Marketplace. Satrang, today, for some awesome Indian food.

I didn’t think I could enjoy Harpreet and Jason’s food more, but I was quite mistaken. As he gave me my usual combo plate of palak paneer, organic chicken curry, lemon rice and naan, Jason asked if I wanted some cumin hot sauce with it and, as I hadn’t had this sauce before, I said sure. (These enterprising young chefs have gone just beyond purveying food from their truck and expanded into sauce creation, with their Chutney Swamy Foods collection. Currently, they have three: Tamarind Sauce, Sweet Mango Sauce—both of which I have, and this new Cumin Hot Sauce.) I dotted each item in the combo plate with a couple drops of the cumin sauce and, after but a couple of bites sat there in the crimson shade totally flabbergasted. It was an incredible, absurd revelation.

Already bursting with flavors both subtle and arch, the cumin hot sauce allowed each ingredient of the combo plate to express something else… something intense and forthright, something… whatever the opposite of banal is. Even the zesty lemon rice tasted new somehow, its citrus essence playfully manifesting like some sort of multi-armed Hindu deity. Can you tell I was in food nirvana? ::chuckle:: After savoring and swallowing a couple more bites of the meal, I peremptorily slammed shut the to-go plate and hastened back to the truck, demanding of Jason to sell me a whole bottle, quick. (I grabbed one each of the other 2 sauces, as I know these’ll make great Christmas presents for a couple of discerning eaters I know. ::chuckle::) It took cosmic restraint on my part not to grace my Haleakala smoothie with a couple of sauce dots just to see if the drink would also… evolve. LOL. As I left, I bade Harpreet aloha (Jason had gone off with a shopping cart of what looked like recyclables) and raved to her: “…you know what that sauce will be good in? Falafel!” Which the neighbor truck purveys. That will be for another day. Today, we are Indian. The Lebanese can wait. ;-)

', 'On the first morning of the new year, visited the Maui Jinsha Shinto shrine in Paukukalo, which I'd never seen in all my years here. The current caretaker of the temple told me the story of that extraordinary wood painting: "The Thousand Horses" was painted in 1912. Each of the horses represented an individual who had donated $1 for the construction of the temple. The person's name is written on each horse's saddle. $1 at that time was a huge sum, a princely fortune for the Issei sugarcane field workers who lived in the plantation camps. The paint on much of the surface of the wood is fading, chipped away by time and weather.

", 'Sometimes dusk is a paragon of indifference—things will shade to darkness and oblivion whether we like it or not, and no amount of seeing will stop the loss of light, shape, form, color, texture, thing-ness. But then. The moment we give in to that entropy… all of a sudden dusk becomes immanent: it is the be-all and end-all of your day. Of your days. And, as such, the fact of its vanishing draws the circle closed. The sense of the day retards to the dark, like the dying echo of a piano sonata’s last notes, and you remember the point of your breath once again. Again.

', 'Am drawn to these forms like the proverbial moth to flame: a glassy liquid surface, no breeze to ruffle its face, elements that play with the light: clouds, a gradient sky, landshapes that carve the frame into quadrants, thirds, wholes.

This one is up at elevation somewhere. Somewhere rather unlikely. But when time and weather and happenstance interface just so… the plane of things, the look of the eye, the capturing of it all, becomes an act of sheer magic. At least to me, it does. I never tire of it.

Finding it is only a fraction of the result, luck is largely the thing that holds it together, skill an artifact of age and time. Still, one does have to have the kind of imagination that is in plentiful supply in a child’s mind and in her eye. Bereft of that, the world is a banal place, an entity to just live in, not to expand through.

This evening, as the sun set, was a good example. I shall hold the story to myself, as the caretaker of the place, a Filipino woman short in stature as my mother, bade me keep the secret and, in her sudden telling allowed me temporary mastery of the pond’s verge, the animal-trodden path, the padlocked gate, opened.

', 'interiority, part 2

It is difficult to reconcile such tempered beauty with the chaos that is to come. There will be the empty spaces where some of us will seek our last refuge but even those, I expect, will be tainted by our hands, our intemperate stewardship of all that was good. Our only home.

It’s not easy to gauge the depth and texture of things when they’re in such stark contrast, like this. That ragged curve there is a massive volcano, on whose flanks lie the dreams of some, the histories of many. And if I didn’t tell you, you’d miss this: Venus and Jupiter in the upper right quadrant, bare pixels of light. On that scale, of our solar system, imagination should be constructed.

In the foreground the glassy pond, on whose surface the gradient of early sky recapitulates. As I entered the gate to this preserve, two nene geese accosted me, interrogatively. One, likely the male, distended its wings, stepped to me, uttering a baleful hiss. By the feet of the other, a single gosling. I nodded an apology, walked softly away.

It is impossible to reconcile such fleeting contact with the imperturbable wildness of it all. At the edge of the water, I crouched, framing things with one amateur eye, penetrating it with the cynical other. Looked back to where the creatures had been, and saw, through to the dark, nothing—not motion, not shape, no evidence of the chaos to come.

Dusk beguiles, as always. Don’t do it, she pleaded… don’t cross that road before our flimsy barriers go up. It was as if we could hear them in the dark, their instincts pulling them from the sea to the pond inshore, but before that, this highway.

Once upon a time, my mother and I joined with a group of devoted honu protectors; naturalists, all, even though we came from different walks of life. It would be before dawn, or even shortly after midnight. We’d stand with kerosene lamps or flashlights, cordoning off North Kihei Road as it passes along Ma’alaea Beach, asking motorists kindly to wait—or take the longer route home—so as to not disturb the migration of egg-laying turtles.

It worked for a while, for a few years. And then, the human outcry overweening, a fence was erected instead, to prevent the turtles from their slow crawl inland. For now, it is to be this way and this way only and always, as long as we walk on our two legs and lead with our brains. Who are they, anyway, these inferior species, to dictate what we should or should not do?

But nature has a way of reclaiming itself, in its own time. Before long, the ocean will rise and cover this road, which will melt under the eonic onslaught of waves, wind, water. Sand will accrue, here as elsewhere and, should they endure our stifling presence, the honu will return, to cross once again from death to life. Theirs… …and where echo no words—not ours, no dross of speech, no forking slipperiness of human tongues.

', 'Thank goodness the phone alarm woke me up, as the dream was about to turn into a nightmare. But as I stood over the bathroom sink, blearily washing sleep from my eyes, I remembered that, years ago, I’d hit on the right method to transform the onset of a nightmare into lucid dreaming. Flying was involved, usually. In the segment of dream just before the story could turn into horror, I was gliding down a huge wave, on a boogie board, all the way to the shore. It never broke. 
Likewise, I see this sky now, and am able to capture it in a series of dreamlike moments; my hands and feet moving my body from one subtle place to the next, angling myself just so… so as to capture the folds and phrases of the early morning, unspooling itself before me like wordless dreaming.

', 'Until they could sit together at some nameless table at an undesignated time, at random, sharing a thoughtfully-crafted ale, there would be a lapse of knowing.

He is going about his life, in serene innocence; I would not have it any other way. (There will be time aplenty to ponder, perhaps to grieve; and, of course, to find again and somehow the joy in what once was.) Once upon a time, my father found himself thrust on the precipice-edge of a mortal dilemma: to deny what he saw with his very own eyes, lest he never see his family again. He chose, painfully… but, in the hindsight of decades later, wisely. He would see things like the mirror image of cloud and sky on the surface of a blissed-out pond perched rather unlikely upon the shoulders of a hill, just like this. He thought he never would. But it came with a price.

He does not know, nor will he ever, what it took for me to find him. There was a kind of death involved, in the way that oppressed peoples find themselves living in the dreadful day-to-day. I see that kind of dispensation threatening now, in the sordid risk of this American presidency. I do have hope that his base and banal instincts will still be dashed on the shoals of the law.

It was something else my father faced, in a culture and history far away… but o lord is it dreadfully, frighteningly, familiar. I sit here, wishing a gentle unremarkable future on my own son but I feel that time has come, and gone. So, a state of innocence, now, is good. That I once held when dad faced that mirroring abyss.

", 'Moonrise, 17 February 2019.

Away from the tempest of time, this. Crouching, I wait on the intersection of sun setting behind me and the wind-stilled pond, the painted clouds, a risen moon generous in its way.

Innocent of the claims on my consciousness, that singular satellite takes the light and hurls it straight at me, my vision halved: seeing, and nothingness. Two sides of the same face.

There are things to contemplate, but also  dread to allay. Mortality a serpent coiled ‘round my neck, biding its time, jealous of nothing and no one. It is the moon, on whom I wait, watch, see.

I bend down to peer at the glassy sand, willing the occlusion of years away, in an effort to recover the sound of her voice, the gentle fall of her footsteps on the incipient day. It wasn't so long ago, yesterday being but a fragment of a figment of time and the very essence of maya. So I do remember her smile, as if it had been given but a moment ago, and the dark yields to an easy exhalation of breath, a simple incantation: here, now, be.

", '1 • ma’alaea
...the blue: from sky above, the ocean below, arrowed sheet of horizon coming straight to my eyes, and from the inside: once upon a time in early childhood there was a sound akin to something so intimate it reminded me of nothing less than the hiss and plash of the world outside the womb: we were on a narrow road, in a jeepney, on an island, approaching the sea for my first time and it was waves: the sound of waves on a beach, white noise of the universe: sea, wind, water, sand and i am brought reverentially back to that moment from here where i stand: on this beach, ma’alaea, the interpenetration of color and memory forcing me away from the thingness of body, the passage of time, the sensation of place, the essence of blue.
', '2 • maui
…that dream the other night: in it i had told her it was nothing like i’d ever felt before, as i held her close, then i told him it was a secret i’d never divulged to anyone but now was doing it to him, for them, as i held him closer: then shortly, when we moved to form the circle and to hold hands before yielding forward: a child interposed himself, asking me to hold him, and then suddenly the whole world felt right in a way it had never been before: it was us, maui, in that moment of longing and sadness and love and loss and all became clear and understood: prayerfully, manifestly, one: without the physicality of being but with the most complete knowing that had ever possessed me, in waking or in dream.
', '3 • hawai’i
…this place: when we arrived here, near to 40 years ago, it did feel like coming home, finally and with a sense of rightness that defied any logic: not that of history, of  resistance, of escape, of revolution: here, at last, we had come to a place of refuge, like so many had done before us in search of a different life but hoping for the same manifestations of cloth, plant, music, love: taken in hand by the vagaries and nuances of life in a different archipelago, the alien words nevertheless strung with familiar sounds, syllables, sensations: these were islands atop an invisible but manifestly powerful spot on the surface of the planet that defined just one thing, hawaii’i: our longed-for, beloved, eternal, place.

...the earthen and elemental beauty of all this is such that there is a ringing in me right now: something is vibrating to the awe-ful spirit of things and has found me at long last it has found me: that it speaks of a deepening existential crisis to our kind, ensconced both subtly and permanently to the outer skin of our home planet is something that by rights should paralyze: but instead it galvanizes, in the sound of these crashing waves a reminder that the notions of the children, unencumbered by the hoary leather of cynical adulthood, are to be welcomed: as the possessors of hope that they are, poised as we all are between the infinite catalepsis of nothingness and the familiar, old, young, thingness of this earth.

", "If you follow me here on FB or Instagram, you know that I hadn't posted many images from my time up at the mauna several weeks ago. And it's mostly because I considered it a spiritual experience, not to be diluted with an inordinate focus on image-making and -sharing. I believe I posted just enough updates to give a sense of where I was—but not really what I was doing and experiencing up there. It’s been 3 weeks from it, and I’m still processing the whole thing… i.e., remembering, thinking, meditating, writing, memorizing—pule, oli, mele, hula.

This noon’s protocol at the UH Maui piko was startling: I was a bit late to it, the pu had been blown and they’d already started the E Kānehoalani and I chanted along as I walked up to the group of about a couple dozen people and found myself standing beside: LANAKILA MANGAUIL. Can you imagine the mana radiating off him and onto me as he said the pule and oli?! ::chuckle:: I didn’t think he was going to be there, but I knew he was going to be here today as they said he’d be giving a hula and oli workshop later this afternoon—which made me scramble yesterday evening and beg Jody to sub for me at the MIL Volleyball matches I was scheduled to ref this evening at Maui HS. To my utter delight, he can. (Mahalo, braddah! I owe you one.) Anyway, I thought to look over some photos from when I was at Moku o Keawe, and find one to accompany this note on the exhilarating* noon protocol today. It’s of Mauna A Wākea in the distance foregrounded by all that ancient lava flowing down to the South Kohala side of things. (*It can’t be anything but that when you have the voice of a kumu hula and kia’i bringing the oli to life, have the elegant sweep and lightning of his hands as he sounds the pahu — all of which then finds an extension and meaning in the suddenly mana-filled landscapes of your own allied hands, feet, voice, na’au.)
", 'This evening at the piko of the UH Maui campus, about a hundred or so of us were taught a powerful hula that was instrumental in the stopping of the construction of the Thirty-Meter Telescope back in April of 2015. That may sound, to the unsuspecting ear, like a thoroughly ridiculous thing to say; but that observation is backed by the simple, impermeable solidity of historical fact: the last line before the construction crews could proceed up to the summit of Mauna Kea was… a line of kia’i, kūpuna, kanaka, dancing this hula with steadfast resolve and the immobility of mauna. Lanakila’s 65-year old mother had the bruises to show for it on her body—so fiercely did she do this hula—which she texted to him… while he was at the Temple of the Oracle in Delphi. Yeah, that one, in Greece. ::chuckle:: So Lanakila taught us all the hula “O hanau ka mauna o Kea,” a mele hanau (birth chant) for Kauikeaouli, Kamehameha III. It is a description of Mauna Kea in a genealogical context. Among many other things, this young kia’i and kumu hula is a brilliant teacher, and within an hour had taught us, the assembled kanaka and hoaloha, an extraordinary thing indeed. We will carry this wherever we now go, won’t we… Torie, Kevin, Teri?

', 'I ka moana … ka moana hōhonu
(from the ocean … the ocean deep)

The sun is not yet here but is already in evidence, in its form of molten water. This is not the color to be found in the deep ocean, although certain bioluminescent creatures in the benthic depths may in fact come garbed in raiments of light that they convey at will, or conceal in exquisite secrecy. Here, at the surface of the planet, on this thin skin of earth and atmosphere, I capture this image only as a symbolic reflection of all that. These words—inadequate; the reality—unspeakably vast.

', 'Where’ve the years gone, my bonny young son… a line from a song half-remembered. 22 yours, 17 of those ours shared. It’s been a dreamlike journey of family—making one where none existed, or was expected. It’s true what is said about love: that it is loss and discovery, empathy and bafflement, silence and voice… and a thousand and twenty-two other things all wrapped up in one embrace that no polemic can sunder. We walk under the lights of this legendary road, the streams of bodies, traffic, commerce and it’s like it always was: together, companionable silence, amusing observations, words half-rendered as we know what the other is thinking. So then I am growing old, and you just starting out, but I do remember the thrill, the fear, the substance of it all. With every breath left to me, then, I wish you: life, love, joy.

I do not know their names, as the article I took it from didn’t have them. And on the other side of the sign, which I had a fellow resister hold up, is a message to Jeff Sessions. What used to say “F” You… now says “Shame on” You. BUT… the F is still there, just very light gray and overlaid with the new words. ::chuckle:: I had gotten the anger out of my system, and several wonderful conversations I had in the days since I posted a picture of the sign made evident to me that it is indeed not pono to become who we despise. That said, the (necessary) anger and rage is still there… just… beneath the surface of things. (The woman holding my sign is Julia, and her dog is Miley. I gave her [the dog] a drink from my water bottle, as it was hot and humid. She lapped it up from my cupped hands, with great thirst and simple animal joy.)

', 'At a little past 1 on this Saturday afternoon the sea west of Keawala’i is a metallic shade of turquoise, its surface perturbed by advance elements of Hurricane Hector (Cat. 3) somewhere southeast of the islands, churning this way with strengthening, easy malevolence. (Last night I called Pono on O’ahu to suggest that he and his cousins spend part of the weekend stocking up on water and other supplies, in the event Hector escalates to a 4 or even 5 by the time it appears in our ambit sometime early next week.) The view from here, glimpsed from this low lavarock parapet, asserts that the ocean is innocent—for now; but that it could emerge from its quiet… entirely heedless of our animal angsts and, as it has always done, manifest its sway over all our affairs, without time, and beyond it. Past this vista, then, a disquieting, still-invisible, storm. There is much to be disturbed about the prevailing human predicament—I suppose this is as it always has been. But the fraying climate worries me the most, as it speaks in gestures far beyond any of our collective will to prevent, mitigate.

I will be dead long before the worst of the consequences of our failed stewardship of this planet but this gives me no keening solace: for, after all, our children will still be here and then, theirs.
', "Early at work this morning because it's going to be a long day full of work, but ending with a glorious choral concert at Keawala'i this evening. Am looking out at Hurricane Hector skies above Iao Church and Wailuku...
", 'Mid-morning, Saturday, August 11 — primary election day in Hawaii nei (although many have already voted early, in the days and weeks prior). Very low tide, at half past 10. The view of the ocean here never fails to stop me in my tracks. Right this moment, the dappled quality of turquoise and bluegreen arrests. I feel in this scene a dangerous* scrim in the existential play of climate change; it is a drama playing itself out all over the planet right now, and the analyses and prognoses by those in the know is grim. (*I say it is ‘dangerous’ because the lambent quality of it can easily lull one into thinking nothing is amiss—but something is most definitely so.)
', 'This lustrous, silverine sky above Makena at the moment — 3:37 p.m., Saturday the 18th — hinting of another hurricane approaching from the southeast...
', 'I am—inescapably, ineluctably—drawn to these empty, sun-written bays... as would you, were you here.
']

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ The girls love their Great Grandpa Steed! Bruce David Steed is one of my main hero’s and I count it as an honor to bear his name. He is always happy, willing to serve, funny, and a great example to those around him!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
He is a follower of Christ, husband, math teacher, father of 8, fixer-upper, grandfather, painter, really good under-ducker (I know from childhood experience on the old acreage swing), hard worker, stealer of his own grandkids’ ice cream, calf deliverer (and brander), lifelong learner, maker of magical childhoods, great-grandfather, wood bird carver, creative thinker, and servant to all… to name a few minor attributes😉
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Now, back to Bruce’s Kickapoo JoyJuice… I remember tearing up every time I drank it as a kid; it was sooo carbonated & yeasty😖 Somehow tough, I always sought it out at the next family reunion, and eventually I cultivated a taste for it!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I aspire to be like my grandpa in so many ways ⬆️see list above⬆️. So, I was thrilled when Lyndsey suggested I should make labels to cover the A&W root beer bottles. I still need to learn the recipe from the old silver fox himself, but for today it was fun to pay tribute to him by having some Kickapoo JoyJuice of our own!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
∾⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
T

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

', 'Some things are improved by digital, like the ease of sharing this photo. Other things, like lens flare… not so much. Never been a fan of the digital artifacts from lens flare on my phone, especially the #LittleGreenDot …also, #tbTuesday to Spring Break at #TobyCreek #InvermereBC (p.s. apparently [new to me] is the fact that Instagram has drafts… this was sitting there for the last 3.5 months)
', 'All real, all today, all #nofilter @pacificsands #staypacificsands #pacificsandscontest
', '3 years later… still hanging around the #SavilleSportsCentre This time it’s her turn to play though!
', 'I am grateful for Lyndsey (@lyndseyolsen). She is incredibly smart, very accomplished, a consummate professional, a pursuer of excellence… and naturally radiant! Basically everything she sets her mind to turns out amazingly, and… she also has an incredible intuition for beautiful days and adventures that shouldn’t be missed! It’s hard to imagine what life would have been like if she ended up going to UVic instead of UofA! #GiveThanks
', 'Yesterday felt glorious! It was hovering just above freezing, but with the brilliant sun it felt really quite balmy! 

I had just spent a goodly amount time standing in a huge line at Costco to get groceries and had come up short on TP (though the cart was otherwise quite full)… as I exited the building the feeling of the sun on my face hinted at what was coming.

As I pushed the cart through the slushy parking lot I was overwhelmed by a positive feeling! I felt grateful to have health, family, food to eat, and a planet that really is amenable to human life when compared to other options!

I was also grateful for all the snow and colder weather that preceded that moment which had the effect of sweetening that sunny-day-feeling!

#GiveThanks
', 'I love the sky… sunsets, clouds, rain, snow, sun dogs, rainbows… all of it! The colours, texture, and grandeur of it all (from up high, or down low) is sure to leave me elevated in spirit!
#GiveThanks
', 'Grateful for an adventure-mobile that fits our family perfectly, amazing places in our own province to visit, summer-vibes, a big ol’ tent, cousins,  #Waterton, and that magical-black-box-à-la-Mary-Poppins-bag to carry extra stuff!
#GiveThanks
']

24: Isolation
', 'More jumping off things, apparently tonight he is pterodactyl.
', 'Fina’s Modern Life #mcrisoproject
', 'Chilled
', 'Isolation Project: Self Portrait

For our second isolation project we were tasked with taking a self portrait. 
In the portrait we should include something that has been with us in isolation or that represents our isolation. 
I chose emotion. 
Our emotions are always with us and I’ve taken the time during isolation to try and really understand my emotional state and acknowledge it. 
What you see is a story, starting with silliness flowing to boredom, depression and anger. 
Then follows acceptance and a will to take charge of an emotional state. Which then evolves to seeking support from those around you, leading to light and happiness. 
I’ve included the before images and the final edited images. 
To make the edits I used Affinity Photo for iPad. 
In the images I used a darker colour palate for the “negative” emotions, which get gradually darker and grainier as they progress. 
As the emotional state moves into a more positive mental state the images get lighter, brighter and the light becomes more intense. 
All photos where taken using an iPhone 11 Pro Max using the wide lens, the iPhone was on a tripod using a remote shutter and the light is provided by a large window for ambient light and an additional adjustable key light. 
For the record I think it’s important to not think of less desired emotions as “negative”. While they can feel that way at the time it’s important to see that without them we would never feel happiness. We all have dark times, it’s good to acknowledge and accept them and to deal with them. 
#mcrisoproject

', 'When corona was still just something to have with lime.

Crazy how fast things happened. One week you’re like ‘yeah it’s just a flu, who cares’ and then it hits you. It’s a lot more. The freedom you got used to is suddenly gone, and worrying becomes a daily pastime.
So now, everyday I count my blessings. I have love, security and health.
Do the same and stay healthy everyone. Let’s ride this one out together, with compassion and understanding. This is not the time to hate or judge. Help each other, be kind. There are many who have it worse. ❤️

', 'Truth be told. I always thought that pregnancy would mean (besides many less shallow things) that I’d for once be able to look at myself without judging the extra fat on my tummy or the bum that could do with some extra squats (or any at all). Don’t get me wrong, l’m proud of my growing belly and I show it off in tight dresses. Plus, I have a lovely man (and many friends) that tell me how beautiful I look daily. Yet I look in envy at those pregnant girls rightfully showing off their gorgeous bodies online with so much confidence. While when I pass a mirror, my eyes will still firstly judge those softening areas that have nothing to do with growing a baby and everything with the cookies I’m stuffing down my face.
So, to turn this around, to look at this body with just the pride it deserves, and to create an ever lasting memory of this incredible, special and beautiful time in the lives of myself and @surfguidealgarve , I asked the grande @massimopardiniphotography to document it and make me feel pretty. ', 'In true PT fashion we were not allowed on the street after 23:00, but there was still a great firework show out on the square at 00:00 ;-)

So we try to follow the rules in hopes to keep this virus at bay. But by all means, for us personally, 2020 has been very kind. We ‘aced’ being in lockdown together, kept our job/business, bought ourselves our first home and soon we’ll bring a new grommet into this world. So 2021, bring it on! ', 'Hark! 
Being colorblind, I’ve always felt hesitation when it comes to sharing colored work. I’ve felt most hesitation with red and green which are both in this drawing. With time, I’ve become less afraid of playing with color and sharing my work. It’s really been fun playing with color and seeing how it’s helped me see color better. 
The fun mystery is wondering how my colors look to normal visioned people.

', 'Pre adding cognac! #happyholidays #happychristmas
', 'So thankful to accept a TOYO! (Ten Outstanding Young Omahans!) award tonight. Love my friends who were there to help me celebrate!
', "Warner Chamber at the Unicameral is so beautiful. I'll be starting at this during some homophobic and transphobic testimony today while I wait to give my support for Sen. Hunt's bill to ban conversion therapy.
", "Let's actually hold up these ideals by passing a non discrimination law that includes gender identity and sexual orientation.
", 'Trampled by Turtles outside in amazing weather!
', 'Wonder wonder indeed!

', 'Holiday lights and train at Lauritzen for UNO night! #KnowTheO
', 'Time to up my work from home game. No more trying to work from the couch. Thankful to have a big dining table for my work station for the foreseeable future, and a bar cart for a bookshelf. Who needs a formal dining area during a pandemic?
', 'If I’m going to be in Menard’s on a Sunday, I’m gonna cope in whatever ways I can. Twinkly lights are a must this year.

', 'LGBTQ+ youth experiencing homelessness face terrifying rates of physical and sexual violence: 62% of LGBTQ+ youth experiencing homelessness reported experiencing physical assault and 38% of LGBTQ+ youth experiencing homelessness reported experiencing sexual assault. @blackandpinkorg ‘s Opportunity Campus will fight against these horrifying numbers by creating a space where LGBTQ+ youth will have access to safety and affirmation. Please join me in contributing as we build toward a world where all LGBTQ+ young people have access to safety and health - link in my bio! #OpportunityCampus #SupportLGBTQYouth #TransLiberation #QueerLiberation #CommunityCare
', 'Got to see one of my very best friends during this trip to Alabama, and it was one of the highlights of this trip for sure. Love ya Libs!
', 'Time for purple hair.
', 'Moved to the grass to enjoy the keynote from our elder Miss Major! #mthf21
', 'My grandmother painted both of these in probably the 70s. Bob Ross eat your heart out.
', 'Courtesy of Alex at Tattoo Expressions.  Tattoo reads “my existence is resistance”.
', 'When queer folks like sports.
', 'Get you a Good Judy like my pal Josh who lends you books like this when you visit. He’s my kinda queer history nerd.
']
